arch community as the majority of them have not been formally published, and exist only as a group of unfinished essays and material for courses on economics taught by Lonergan. Lonergan's economic ideas track a different line of thought from that taken by contemporary economists. Macroeconomic Dynamics: An Essay in Circulation Analysis represents the economic thought of Lonergan at the end of his career. His analysis, while taking a fresh look at fundamental variables, breaks from centralist theory and practice towards a radically democratic perspective on surplus income and non-political control, and explores more fully the ideas introduced in For a New Political Economy. This work will be read not only by economists but also by liberation theologians, political theologians, and others inside and outside of religious organizations interested in social justice issues and alternative approaches to economics.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aEconomics. 0aMacroeconomics. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Political.2bisacsh1 aByrne, Patrick, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aCrowe, Frederick E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDoran, Robert M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHefling, Charles C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHefling, Jr., Charles, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aLawrence, Frederick, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press eBook-Package Archive 1933-1999z978311049094740uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978144267687940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781442676879423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781442676879.jpg  a978-3-11-049094-7  University of